        illustrationCaption: 'An Emberth forger with cooled volcanic charcoal skin and dreadlocks, holding a bright, hot ember in their hand.',
        description: 'Broad-shouldered and deliberate, the Emberth move through the ashlands like men who have already decided where the ground will be. Their skin — deep brown to near-black, leather-tough from centuries scraping against volcanic stone — bears the grain of a people who spent generations underground and emerged with the silence still in their bones. Their hair, jet-black and coarse as forge-rope, is shorn short — a mark of forge-discipline, fire-hazard caution in enclosed chambers. The Thrask, who range the frozen surface, wear theirs longer for insulation against the cold. Neither braids it. Their identity is carried elsewhere: in the deliberate burn-scars on their forearms, mapped like a forge-record of clan, trade, and lineage. Their eyes are too large for their faces — a legacy of the lightless thermal caverns where they sheltered after Sol was entombed — and they squint constantly on the surface, wrapped in ash-tinted eye-cloths that give them the look of perpetual mourners. They are not mourners. They are keepers of a vigil.',
        icon: 'fas fa-fire',
        overview: `When Sol spoke to us, it was never in words. The Sun-Speakers — our elders, our prophets, our bridge to the dying god — crouched in the volcanic vents at dawn and received what Sol was willing to give: pulses of heat, fragments of image, a sense of descent and darkness and a great digging that translated poorly into language but urgently into action. We dug. While the seven noble families debated their rituals and their bargains, while Keth-Amar circled the dying sun like a scavenger above wounded prey, we excavated the thermal deep beneath Sundale — not knowing what we were preparing for, only that Sol had told us to prepare.

We were already underground when the surface froze. On the day Sol was bound beneath the earth's crust by the noble families' desperate ritual, every Sun-Speaker in every clan received the same final image: an ember held in cupped hands. Then silence. Sol has not spoken since. We call that ember the Solbrand — a small, eternal flame we have tended through centuries of darkness — and we do not know if it is Sol's last conscious fragment or something else entirely, something Keth-Amar left behind when it breached the seal and began its slow, patient feast on the god we failed to protect.

We emerged when Emberspire erupted. We reclaimed the ashland surface our ancestors once walked beneath open sky. We rebuilt our forge-clans around the geothermal vents, resumed the old ways — sun-prayers at dawn, forge-work as devotion, the Solbrand tended by an order of Sun-Speakers who listen every morning to a silence that has lasted centuries. We are not forge-people because fire is in our blood. We are forge-people because Sol gave us the Solbrand and we do not know what else to do with our hands.`,
        culturalBackground: `Emberth society is organized into forge-clans bound to volcanic calderas — each clan tracing its lineage to one of the original Sun-Speakers who received the prophecy of descent. These clans are not factions or competing nations. They are bloodlines, each with its own ancestral forge, its own variant of the sun-prayers, its own interpretation of the silence Sol left behind. Clan identity is worn visibly: every Emberth's forearms and shoulders are marked at birth with deliberate burn-scars applied by a heated obsidian stylus — a process called the Marking-Rite. The scars encode clan affiliation, trade specialization, and ancestor-lineage in a visual language that can be read by any Emberth at a glance. The marks darken with proximity to the Solbrand; Korr forge-marks are stark and crisp, while Thrask marks are fainter and blurred at the edges from generational distance from the ember. To deface a forge-mark is the severest crime.

Settlements are built around the forges — not as industry, but as altars. The forge is where the Solbrand is kept by the clan currently entrusted with its tending; where young Emberth are brought at dawn to learn stillness before they learn speech; where disputes are settled not by violence but by forge-trials — competitions of craft, endurance, or hours of uninterrupted silence before the flame. The skills vary by clan. The principle is the same: Sol's silence taught the Emberth patience, and patience is the highest virtue.

The surface ashlands are barely hospitable to anyone else — choking storms of volcanic particulate sweep across Sundale in seasons — but the Emberth breathe them comfortably. Their lungs adapted across generations of underground exile, developing thick mucosal membranes that filter ash from air. The cost: in clean, humid climates, their lungs grow sluggish and heavy. They breathe easiest in the smoke of their own forges. An Emberth in a forest is a soldier in enemy territory.

Their society is a meritocracy of craft and endurance, not birth. Those who work longest, forge finest, endure deepest silence rise highest. The weak are not cast out — they are pitied, supported, given simpler work, because weakness in one clan-member shames the entire bloodline. The greatest terror in Emberth culture is not death. It is the slow, permanent cooling of the Solbrand — a dimming that has been observed, denied, concealed, and whispered about across three generations. The clan that currently holds the Solbrand has been lying about its health. The other clans are beginning to splinter. What happens when the last ember of Sol goes out is a question no Emberth knows how to answer.`,
        variantDiversity: 'The Emberth are divided into two bloodlines based on where their ancestors sheltered during the underground exile: the Korr of the Deep-Vault, who chose to tend the Solbrand and wait for Sol\'s return, and the Thrask of the High-Vault, who chose to range the frozen surface border and keep the other clans fed. These were not ideological choices but spatial ones — the caverns were not uniform, and the Growth-Grain calcified each bloodline differently across centuries. Both forge. Both pray at the Solstice Vigil. Their forearms bear the same forge-mark scars. But the Deep-Vault made the Korr still and fragile, and the surface border made the Thrask swift and cold-hardened.',
